   <h1>RE: [T2] Fuel line from Lowe's(was Gas leak)</h1>
   <b>George Lyle &lt;glyle_at_lenti.type2_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2001-01-17 23:05:41+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>

On Wed, 17 Jan 2001, Jaime Chriswisser wrote:

> 
> <Scott.Solomon_at_mcchord.af_dot_mil> wrote:
> > But some aftermarket carbs
> > use the 1/4in or 5/16in fuel line and it will be
> > great for those. With a
> > 200psi working pressure, it will handle any
> > carborated fuel system out
> > there. 
> 
> Still a bad idea, IMHO, as the fitting on your stock
> fuel pump is still metric. What happens when you try
> to clamp a larger diameter hose on a smaller fitting,
> is actually creating a gap in the hose (where the
> excess material is scrunched together)...this will
> eventually allow *some* fuel to penetrate. Not much;
> you might not even notice it...but eventualy, the line
> will come loose. Not good. Especially for us upright
> owners, where the fuel pump is located next to that
> sparky little thing called a dizzy;-)
> 
> It's far better to stretch the proper diameter hose
> over the larger fittings, than to risk a fire.
> 
> 
> When I first bought my '69 Westy, a VW mechanic friend
> immediately noticed the new, but non-stock fuel line.
> Without saying a word, he went in his shop, came back
> with the proper hose and replaced it. He charged me
> for the hose, and said, 'Trust me, you'll thank me
> later'.

I was thinking about this and pulled out the calculator.  A 1/4 inch hose
as an ID of 0.250 in.  6mm converts to an ID of 0.236 inch.  The
difference is .014 inch.

I've seen a greater variation than this in the fuel inlets/outlets on
various lines, pumps, and carburators on VWs.  The metric hose fits a tiny
bit tighter, but one should still be careful of the fit, regardless of the
hose used.  If the hose is a good friction fit it will make a good seal.
If it slides on with little effort, the seal won't be all that good, even
with clamps.</pre>


